# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hydrogels-bio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] It is a significant component of the biofilms produced by the bacterium *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, a major pathogen found in the lungs of some people who have cystic fibrosis.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] The biofilm and *P. aeruginosa* have a high resistance to antibiotics, but are susceptible to inhibition by macrophages.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Alginate was discovered by the British chemical scientist E.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Stanford in 1881, and he patented an extraction process for it in the same year.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] The alginate was extracted, in the original patent, by first soaking the algae in water or diluted acid.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] The resulting insoluble alginic acid is then treated with an alkaline solution such as sodium carbonate, creating sodium alginate, before finally precipitating and purifying the alginate from solution.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Alginic acid is a linear copolymer with homopolymeric blocks of (1→4)-linked β-D-mannuronate (M) and α-L-guluronate (G) residues, respectively, covalently linked together in different sequences or blocks.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] The monomers may appear in homopolymeric blocks of consecutive G-residues (G-blocks), consecutive M-residues (M-blocks) or alternating M and G-residues (MG-blocks). α-L-guluronate is the C-5 epimer of β-D-mannuronate.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Alginates are refined from brown seaweeds.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Throughout the world, many of the Phaeophyceae class brown seaweeds are harvested to be processed and converted into sodium alginate.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Sodium alginate is used in many industries including food, animal food, fertilisers, textile printing, and pharmaceuticals.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Dental impression material uses alginate as its means of gelling.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Food grade alginate is an approved ingredient in processed and manufactured foods.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Brown seaweeds range in size from the giant kelp *Macrocystis pyrifera* which can be 20–40 meters long, to thick, leather-like seaweeds from 2–4 m long, to smaller species 30–60 cm long.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Most brown seaweed used for alginates are gathered from the wild, with the exception of *Laminaria japonica*, which is cultivated in China for food and its surplus material is diverted to the alginate industry in China.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Alginates from different species of brown seaweed vary in their chemical structure, resulting in different physical properties of alginates.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Some species yield an alginate that gives a strong gel, another a weaker gel, some may produce a cream or white alginate, while others are difficult to gel and are best used for technical applications where color does not matter.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Commercial grade alginate is extracted from giant kelp *Macrocystis pyrifera*, *Ascophyllum nodosum*, and types of *Laminaria*.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Alginates are also produced by two bacterial genera *Pseudomonas* and *Azotobacter*, which played a major role in the unravelling of its biosynthesis pathway.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Bacterial alginates are useful for the production of micro- or nanostructures suitable for medical applications.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Sodium alginate (NaC6H7O6) is the sodium salt of alginic acid.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Potassium alginate (KC6H7O6) is the potassium salt of alginic acid.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Calcium alginate (CaC12H14O12) is the calcium salt of alginic acid.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] It is made by replacing the sodium ion in sodium alginate with a calcium ion (ion exchange).
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Chemically the process is simple, but difficulties arise from the physical separations required between the slimy residues from viscous solutions and the separation of gelatinous precipitates that hold large amounts of liquid within their structure, so they resist filtration and centrifugation.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] The conventional process involves large amounts of reagents and solvents, as well as time-consuming steps.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Simpler and newer techniques, such as microwave-assisted extraction, ultrasound, high pressure, pressurized fluid extraction, and enzyme-assisted extraction, are the subject of research.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] The most common, conventional extraction process involves six steps: pre-treatment of the algal biomass, acid treatment, alkaline extraction, precipitation, bleaching, and drying.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Pre-treatments mainly aim at either breaking the cell wall to help extract the alginate, or removing other compounds and contaminants from the algae.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Drying is of the first kind, also helping to prevent bacterial growth; algae which is dried is also usually powdered to expose more surface area.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Common treatments to remove contaminants include treatments with ethanol and formaldehyde, the latter of which is very common; ethanol solutions help remove compounds bonded to the alginate, and formaldehyde solutions help prevent enzymatic or microbial reactions.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] The algae is then treated with an acidic solution to help disrupt cell walls, which converts the alginate salts into insoluble alginic acid; a subsequently applied alkaline solution (pH 9-10), usually sodium carbonate, converts it back into water-soluble sodium alginate, which is then precipitated.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] It is also possible to extract the alginate directly with an alkaline treatment, but this is less common.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Alginic acid is usually precipitated, through different techniques, with either an alcohol (usually ethanol), calcium chloride, or hydrochloric acid.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] After the alginin is precipitated into a fine paste, it is dried, ground to the desired grain size, and finally purified through a variety of techniques.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Commercial alginate for biomedical and pharmaceutical use is extracted and purified through more rigorous techniques, but these are trade secrets.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Various alginate-based materials can be produced, including porous scaffold material, alginate hydrogel, nonwoven fabric, and alginate membranes.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Techniques used to produce these include ion cross-linking, microfluidic spinning, freeze drying, wet spinning, and immersive centrifugal jet spinning.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Calcium salts added to a sodium alginate solution to induce ionic cross-linking, which produces the hydrogel.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Freeze-drying the hydrogel to eliminate water produces the porous scaffold material.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Wet spinning consists of extruding an alginate solution from a spinneret into a calcium salt solution to induce ionic cross-linking (forming the gel), and then drawing the fibers out of the bath with draft rollers.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Microfluidic spinning, a simpler and more eco-friendly implementation of the process, involves introducing calcium salt flows flowing alongside and touching a central "core" flow of alginate.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] The fiber then emerges from the core flow.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] This technique can be used to produce shaped and grooved fibers.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Alginate fiber, which is used in fabric, is usually produced through either microfluidic spinning, wet spinning, or electrospinning to obtain thinner fibers.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Those fibers are used to produce alginate nonwoven fabric by carding and needle punching.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] The resulting felts are used in wound dressings, facial masks, and tissue scaffolds due to its hygroscopic and water retention ability.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] As of 2022, alginate had become one of the most preferred materials as an abundant natural biopolymer.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] It is particularly useful as a biomaterial because of its nontoxicity, hygroscopicity, and biocompatibility, and can imitate local bioenvironments; its degradation product can be easily cleared by the kidneys.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Alginate absorbs water quickly, which makes it useful as an additive in dehydrated products such as slimming aids, and in the manufacture of paper and textiles.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Alginate is also used for waterproofing and fireproofing fabrics, in the food industry as a thickening agent for drinks, ice cream, cosmetics, as a gelling agent for jellies, known by the code E401 and sausage casing.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Sodium alginate is mixed with soybean protein to make meat analogue.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Alginate is used as an ingredient in various pharmaceutical preparations, such as Gaviscon, in which it combines with bicarbonate to inhibit gastroesophageal reflux.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Sodium alginate is used as an impression-making material in dentistry, prosthetics, lifecasting, and for creating positives for small-scale casting.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Sodium alginate is used in reactive dye printing and as a thickener for reactive dyes in textile screen-printing.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Alginates do not react with these dyes and wash out easily, unlike starch-based thickeners.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] It also serves as a material for micro-encapsulation.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Calcium alginate is used in different types of medical products, including skin wound dressings, in the form of hydrogels, to promote healing, since alginate can increase the fluid uptake capacity of dressings, reducing the amount of times the dressing needs to be changed.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] In research on bone reconstruction, alginate composites have favorable properties encouraging regeneration, such as improved porosity, cell proliferation, and mechanical strength.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Alginate hydrogel is a common biomaterial for bio-fabrication of scaffolds and tissue regeneration.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Covalent bonding of thiol groups to alginate improves in-situ gelling and mucoadhesive properties; the thiolated polymer (thiomer) forms disulfide bonds within its polymeric network and with cysteine-rich subdomains of the mucus layer.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Thiolated alginates are used as in situ gelling hydrogels, and are under preliminary research as possible mucoadhesive drug delivery systems.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Alginate hydrogels may be used for drug delivery, exhibiting responses to pH changes, temperature changes, redox, and the presence of enzymes.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Alginate is one of the most widely used polymers in bioencapsulation, particularly for the immobilisation or protection of living cells, enzymes, proteins and other bioactive materials.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Its use is largely based on the ability of soluble alginate to form calcium alginate hydrogels under mild aqueous conditions, allowing biological material to be entrapped without exposure to harsh solvents, high temperature or aggressive chemical reactions.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] In cell encapsulation, alginate beads or microcapsules can provide a semipermeable hydrogel matrix that permits diffusion of nutrients, oxygen and secreted products while physically separating the encapsulated cells from the surrounding environment.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] This approach has been investigated for immunoisolation, islet transplantation, cell therapy, tissue engineering and controlled delivery of biological products.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] Alginate bioencapsulation systems can be produced by dripping, extrusion, air-jet cutting, electrostatic droplet generation, emulsification and microfluidic methods.
[src:hydrogels-bio/alginate] These techniques differ in throughput, bead-size control, size distribution and suitability for encapsulating cells or labile biomolecules.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] In chemistry and biology, a **cross-link** is a bond or a short sequence of bonds that links one polymer chain to another.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] These links may take the form of covalent bonds or ionic bonds and the polymers can be either synthetic polymers or natural polymers (such as proteins).
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] In polymer chemistry "cross-linking" usually refers to the use of cross-links to promote a change in the polymers' physical properties.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] When "crosslinking" is used in the biological field, it refers to the use of a probe to link proteins together to check for protein–protein interactions, as well as other creative cross-linking methodologies.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Although the term is used to refer to the "linking of polymer chains" for both sciences, the extent of crosslinking and specificities of the crosslinking agents vary greatly.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Crosslinking generally involves covalent bonds that join two polymer chains.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] The term *curing* refers to the crosslinking of thermosetting resins, such as unsaturated polyester and epoxy resin, and the term *vulcanization* is characteristically used for rubbers.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] When polymer chains are crosslinked, the material becomes more rigid.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] The mechanical properties of a polymer depend strongly on the cross-link density.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Low cross-link densities increase the viscosities of polymer melts.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Intermediate cross-link densities transform gummy polymers into materials that have elastomeric properties and potentially high strengths.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Very high cross-link densities can cause materials to become very rigid or glassy, such as phenol-formaldehyde materials.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] In one implementation, unpolymerized or partially polymerized resin is treated with a **crosslinking reagent**.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] In vulcanization, sulfur is the cross-linking agent.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Its introduction changes rubber to a more rigid, durable material associated with car and bike tires.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] This process is often called sulfur curing.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] In most cases, cross-linking is irreversible, and the resulting thermosetting material will degrade or burn if heated, without melting.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Chemical covalent cross-links are stable mechanically and thermally.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Therefore, cross-linked products like car tires cannot be recycled easily.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] A class of polymers known as thermoplastic elastomers rely on physical cross-links in their microstructure to achieve stability, and are widely used in non-tire applications, such as snowmobile tracks, and catheters for medical use.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] They offer a much wider range of properties than conventional cross-linked elastomers because the domains that act as cross-links are reversible, so can be reformed by heat.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] The stabilizing domains may be non-crystalline (as in styrene-butadiene block copolymers) or crystalline as in thermoplastic copolyesters.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Alkyd enamels, the dominant type of commercial oil-based paint, cure by oxidative crosslinking after exposure to air.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] In contrast to chemical cross-links, physical cross-links are formed by weaker interactions.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] For example, sodium alginate gels upon exposure to calcium ions, which form ionic bonds that bridge between alginate chains.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Polyvinyl alcohol gels upon the addition of borax through hydrogen bonding between boric acid and the polymer's alcohol groups.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Other examples of materials which form physically cross-linked gels include gelatin, collagen, agarose, and agar agar.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Crosslinking is often measured by swelling tests.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] The crosslinked sample is placed into a good solvent at a specific temperature, and either the change in mass or the change in volume is measured.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] The more crosslinking, the less swelling is attainable.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Based on the degree of swelling, the Flory Interaction Parameter (which relates the solvent interaction with the sample), and the density of the solvent, the theoretical degree of crosslinking can be calculated according to Flory's Network Theory.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Two ASTM standards are commonly used to describe the degree of crosslinking in thermoplastics.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] In ASTM D2765, the sample is weighed, then placed in a solvent for 24 hours, weighed again while swollen, then dried and weighed a final time.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] The degree of swelling and the soluble portion can be calculated.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] In another ASTM standard, F2214, the sample is placed in an instrument that measures the height change in the sample, allowing the user to measure the volume change.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] The crosslink density can then be calculated.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Lignin is a highly crosslinked polymer that comprises the main structural material of higher plants.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] A hydrophobic material, it is derived from precursor monolignols.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Heterogeneity arises from the diversity and degree of crosslinking between these lignols.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Intrastrand DNA crosslinks have strong effects on organisms because these lesions interfere with transcription and replication.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] These effects can be put to good use (addressing cancer) or they can be lethal to the host organism.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] The drug cisplatin functions by formation of intrastrand crosslinks in DNA.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Other crosslinking agents include mustard gas, mitomycin, and psoralen.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] In proteins, crosslinks are important in generating mechanically stable structures such as hair and wool, skin, and cartilage.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Isopeptide bond formation is another type of protein crosslink.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] The process of applying a permanent wave to hair involves the breaking and reformation of disulfide bonds.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Typically a mercaptan such as ammonium thioglycolate is used for the breaking.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Following this, the hair is curled and then "neutralized".
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] The neutralizer is typically an acidic solution of hydrogen peroxide, which causes new disulfide bonds to form, thus permanently fixing the hair into its new configuration.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Compromised collagen in the cornea, a condition known as keratoconus, can be treated with clinical crosslinking.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] In biological context crosslinking could play a role in atherosclerosis through advanced glycation end-products (AGEs), which have been implicated to induce crosslinking of collagen, which may lead to vascular stiffening.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Proteins can also be cross-linked artificially using small-molecule crosslinkers.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] This approach has been used to elucidate protein–protein interactions.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Crosslinkers bind only surface residues in relatively close proximity in the native state.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Common crosslinkers include the imidoester crosslinker dimethyl suberimidate, the N-Hydroxysuccinimide-ester crosslinker BS3 and formaldehyde.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Each of these crosslinkers induces nucleophilic attack of the amino group of lysine and subsequent covalent bonding via the crosslinker.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] The zero-length carbodiimide crosslinker EDC functions by converting carboxyls into amine-reactive isourea intermediates that bind to lysine residues or other available primary amines.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] SMCC or its water-soluble analog, Sulfo-SMCC, is commonly used to prepare antibody-hapten conjugates for antibody development.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] An *in-vitro* cross-linking method is PICUP (photo-induced cross-linking of unmodified proteins).
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Typical reagents are ammonium persulfate (APS), an electron acceptor, the photosensitizer tris-bipyridylruthenium (II) cation ([Ru(bpy)3]2+).
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] In *in-vivo* crosslinking of protein complexes, cells are grown with photoreactive diazirine analogs to leucine and methionine, which are incorporated into proteins.
[src:hydrogels-bio/cross-link] Upon exposure to ultraviolet light, the diazirines are activated and bind to interacting proteins that are within a few ångströms of the photo-reactive amino acid analog (UV cross-linking).
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] A **hydrogel** is a biphasic material, a mixture of porous and permeable solids and at least 10% of water or other interstitial fluid.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The solid phase is a water insoluble three dimensional network of polymers, having absorbed a large amount of water or biological fluids.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Hydrogels have several applications, especially in the biomedical area, such as in hydrogel dressing.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Many hydrogels are synthetic, but some are derived from natural materials.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The crosslinks which bond the polymers of a hydrogel fall under two general categories: physical hydrogels and chemical hydrogels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Chemical hydrogels have covalent cross-linking bonds, whereas physical hydrogels have non-covalent bonds.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Chemical hydrogels can result in strong reversible or irreversible gels due to the covalent bonding.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Chemical hydrogels that contain reversible covalent cross-linking bonds, such as hydrogels of thiomers being cross-linked via disulfide bonds, are non-toxic and are used in numerous medicinal products.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Physical hydrogels usually have high biocompatibility, are not toxic, and are also easily reversible by simply changing an external stimulus such as pH, ion concentration (alginate) or temperature (gelatine); they are also used for medical applications.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Physical crosslinks consist of hydrogen bonds, hydrophobic interactions, and chain entanglements (among others).
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] A hydrogel generated through the use of physical crosslinks is sometimes called a 'reversible' hydrogel.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Chemical crosslinks consist of covalent bonds between polymer strands.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Hydrogels generated in this manner are sometimes called 'permanent' hydrogels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Hydrogels are prepared using a variety of polymeric materials, which can be divided broadly into two categories according to their origin: natural or synthetic polymers.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Natural polymers for hydrogel preparation include hyaluronic acid, chitosan, heparin, alginate, gelatin and fibrin.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Common synthetic polymers include polyvinyl alcohol, polyethylene glycol, sodium polyacrylate, acrylate polymers and copolymers thereof.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Whereas natural hydrogels are usually non-toxic, and often provide other advantages for medical use, such as biocompatibility, biodegradability, antibiotic/antifungal effect and improve regeneration of nearby tissue, their stability and strength is usually much lower than synthetic hydrogels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] There are also synthetic hydrogels that can be used for medical applications, such as polyethylene glycol (PEG), polyacrylate, and polyvinylpyrrolidone (PVP).
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] There are two suggested mechanisms behind physical hydrogel formation, the first one being the gelation of nanofibrous peptide assemblies, usually observed for oligopeptide precursors.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The precursors self-assemble into fibers, tapes, tubes, or ribbons that entangle to form non-covalent cross-links.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The second mechanism involves non-covalent interactions of cross-linked domains that are separated by water-soluble linkers, and this is usually observed in longer multi-domain structures.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Tuning of the supramolecular interactions to produce a self-supporting network that does not precipitate, and is also able to immobilize water is vital for gel formation.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Most oligopeptide hydrogels have a β-sheet structure, and assemble to form fibers, although α-helical peptides have also been reported.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] In a typical mechanism of gelation, oligopeptide precursors self-assemble into fibers that become elongated, and entangle to form cross-linked gels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] One notable method of initiating a polymerization reaction involves the use of light as a stimulus.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] In this method, photoinitiators, compounds that cleave from the absorption of photons, are added to the precursor solution which will become the hydrogel.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] When the precursor solution is exposed to a concentrated source of light, usually ultraviolet irradiation, the photoinitiators will cleave and form free radicals, which will begin a polymerization reaction that forms crosslinks between polymer strands.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] This reaction will cease if the light source is removed, allowing the amount of crosslinks formed in the hydrogel to be controlled.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The properties of a hydrogel are highly dependent on the type and quantity of its crosslinks, making photopolymerization a popular choice for fine-tuning hydrogels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] This technique has seen considerable use in cell and tissue engineering applications due to the ability to inject or mold a precursor solution loaded with cells into a wound site, then solidify it in situ.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Physically crosslinked hydrogels can be prepared by different methods depending on the nature of the crosslink involved.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Polyvinyl alcohol hydrogels are usually produced by the freeze-thaw technique.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] In this, the solution is frozen for a few hours, then thawed at room temperature, and the cycle is repeated until a strong and stable hydrogel is formed.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Alginate hydrogels are formed by ionic interactions between alginate and double-charged cations.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] A salt, usually calcium chloride, is dissolved into an aqueous sodium alginate solution, that causes the calcium ions to create ionic bonds between alginate chains.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Gelatin hydrogels are formed by temperature change.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] A water solution of gelatin forms an hydrogel at temperatures below 37–35 °C, as Van der Waals interactions between collagen fibers become stronger than thermal molecular vibrations.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Peptide based hydrogels possess exceptional biocompatibility and biodegradability qualities, giving rise to their wide use of applications, particularly in biomedicine; as such, their physical properties can be fine-tuned in order to maximise their use.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Methods to do this are: modulation of the amino acid sequence, pH, chirality, and increasing the number of aromatic residues.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The order of amino acids within the sequence is crucial for gelation, as has been shown many times.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] In one example, a short peptide sequence Fmoc-Phe-Gly readily formed a hydrogel, whereas Fmoc-Gly-Phe failed to do so as a result of the two adjacent aromatic moieties being moved, hindering the aromatic interactions.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Altering the pH can also have similar effects, an example involved the use of the naphthalene (Nap) modified dipeptides Nap-Gly-Ala, and Nap- Ala-Gly, where a drop in pH induced gelation of the former, but led to crystallisation of the latter.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] A controlled pH decrease method using glucono-δ-lactone (GdL), where the GdL is hydrolysed to gluconic acid in water is a recent strategy that has been developed as a way to form homogeneous and reproducible hydrogels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The hydrolysis is slow, which allows for a uniform pH change, and thus resulting in reproducible homogenous gels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] In addition to this, the desired pH can be achieved by altering the amount of GdL added.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The use of GdL has been used various times for the hydrogelation of Fmoc and Nap-dipeptides.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] In another direction, Morris et al reported the use of GdL as a 'molecular trigger' to predict and control the order of gelation.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Chirality also plays an essential role in gel formation, and even changing the chirality of a single amino acid from its natural L-amino acid to its unnatural D-amino acid can significantly impact the gelation properties, with the natural forms not forming gels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Furthermore, aromatic interactions play a key role in hydrogel formation as a result of π- π stacking driving gelation, shown by many studies.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Hydrogels also possess a degree of flexibility very similar to natural tissue due to their significant water content.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] As responsive "smart materials", hydrogels can encapsulate chemical systems which upon stimulation by external factors such as a change of pH may cause specific compounds such as glucose to be liberated to the environment, in most cases by a gel–sol transition to the liquid state.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Chemomechanical polymers are mostly also hydrogels, which upon stimulation change their volume and can serve as actuators or sensors.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Hydrogels have been investigated for diverse applications.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] By modifying the polymer concentration of a hydrogel (or conversely, the water concentration), the Young's modulus, shear modulus, and storage modulus can vary from 10 Pa to 3 MPa, a range of about five orders of magnitude.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] A similar effect can be seen by altering the crosslinking concentration.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] This much variability of the mechanical stiffness is why hydrogels are so appealing for biomedical applications, where it is vital for implants to match the mechanical properties of the surrounding tissues.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Characterizing the mechanical properties of hydrogels can be difficult especially due to the differences in mechanical behavior that hydrogels have in comparison to other traditional engineering materials.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] In addition to its rubber elasticity and viscoelasticity, hydrogels have an additional time dependent deformation mechanism which is dependent on fluid flow called poroelasticity.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] These properties are extremely important to consider while performing mechanical experiments.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Some common mechanical testing experiments for hydrogels are tension, compression (confined or unconfined), indentation, shear rheometry or dynamic mechanical analysis.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] In the unswollen state, hydrogels can be modelled as highly crosslinked chemical gels, in which the system can be described as one continuous polymer network.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] where $\lambda =l_{\textrm {current}}/l_{\textrm {original}}$ is the stretch.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] For hydrogels, their elasticity comes from the solid polymer matrix while the viscosity originates from the polymer network mobility and the water and other components that make up the aqueous phase.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Viscoelastic properties of a hydrogel is highly dependent on the nature of the applied mechanical motion.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Thus, the time dependence of these applied forces is extremely important for evaluating the viscoelasticity of the material.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Physical models for viscoelasticity attempt to capture the elastic and viscous material properties of a material.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] In an elastic material, the stress is proportional to the strain while in a viscous material, the stress is proportional to the strain rate.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The Maxwell model is one developed mathematical model for linear viscoelastic response.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] In this model, viscoelasticity is modeled analogous to an electrical circuit with a Hookean spring, that represents the Young's modulus, and a Newtonian dashpot that represents the viscosity.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] A material that exhibit properties described in this model is a Maxwell material.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Another physical model used is called the Kelvin-Voigt Model and a material that follow this model is called a Kelvin–Voigt material.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] In order to describe the time-dependent creep and stress-relaxation behavior of hydrogel, a variety of physical lumped parameter models can be used.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] These modeling methods vary greatly and are extremely complex, so the empirical Prony Series description is commonly used to describe the viscoelastic behavior in hydrogels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] In order to measure the time-dependent viscoelastic behavior of polymers dynamic mechanical analysis is often performed.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Typically, in these measurements the one side of the hydrogel is subjected to a sinusoidal load in shear mode while the applied stress is measured with a stress transducer and the change in sample length is measured with a strain transducer.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] in which G' is the real (elastic or storage) modulus, G" is the imaginary (viscous or loss) modulus.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Poroelasticity is a characteristic of materials related to the migration of solvent through a porous material and the concurrent deformation that occurs.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Poroelasticity in hydrated materials such as hydrogels occurs due to friction between the polymer and water as the water moves through the porous matrix upon compression.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] This causes a decrease in water pressure, which adds additional stress upon compression.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Similar to viscoelasticity, this behavior is time dependent, thus poroelasticity is dependent on compression rate: a hydrogel shows softness upon slow compression, but fast compression makes the hydrogel stiffer.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] This phenomenon is due to the friction between the water and the porous matrix is proportional to the flow of water, which in turn is dependent on compression rate.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Thus, a common way to measure poroelasticity is to do compression tests at varying compression rates.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Pore size is an important factor in influencing poroelasticity.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The Kozeny–Carman equation has been used to predict pore size by relating the pressure drop to the difference in stress between two compression rates.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Poroelasticity is described by several coupled equations, thus there are few mechanical tests that relate directly to the poroelastic behavior of the material, thus more complicated tests such as indentation testing, numerical or computational models are utilized.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Numerical or computational methods attempt to simulate the three dimensional permeability of the hydrogel network.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The toughness of a hydrogel refers to the ability of the hydrogel to withstand deformation or mechanical stress without fracturing or breaking apart.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] A hydrogel with high toughness can maintain its structural integrity and functionality under higher stress.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Several factors contribute to the toughness of a hydrogel including composition, crosslink density, polymer chain structure, and hydration level.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The toughness of a hydrogel is highly dependent on what polymer(s) and crosslinker(s) make up its matrix as certain polymers possess higher toughness and certain crosslinking covalent bonds are inherently stronger.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Additionally, higher crosslinking density generally leads to increased toughness by restricting polymer chain mobility and enhancing resistance to deformation.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The structure of the polymer chains is also a factor in that, longer chain lengths and higher molecular weight leads to a greater number of entanglements and higher toughness.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] A good balance (equilibrium) in the hydration of a hydrogel leads is important because too low hydration causes poor flexibility and toughness within the hydrogel, but too high of water content can cause excessive swelling, weakening the mechanical properties of the hydrogel.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The hysteresis of a hydrogel refers to the phenomenon where there is a delay in the deformation and recovery of a hydrogel when it is subjected to mechanical stress and relieved of that stress.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] This occurs because the polymer chains within a hydrogel rearrange, and the water molecules are displaced, and energy is stored as it deforms in mechanical extension or compression.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] When the mechanical stress is removed, the hydrogel begins to recover its original shape, but there may be a delay in the recovery process due to factors like viscoelasticity, internal friction, etc.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] This leads to a difference between the stress-strain curve during loading and unloading.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Hysteresis within a hydrogel is influenced by several factors including composition, crosslink density, polymer chain structure, and temperature.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The toughness and hysteresis of a hydrogel are especially important in the context of biomedical applications such as tissue engineering and drug delivery, as the hydrogel may need to withstand mechanical forces within the body, but also maintain mechanical performance and stability over time.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Most typical hydrogels, both natural and synthetic, have a positive correlation between toughness and hysteresis, meaning that the higher the toughness, the longer the hydrogel takes to recover its original shape and vice versa.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] This is largely due to sacrificial bonds being the source of toughness within many of these hydrogels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Sacrificial bonds are non-covalent interactions such as hydrogen bonds, ionic interactions, and hydrophobic interactions, that can break and reform under mechanical stress.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The reforming of these bonds takes time, especially when there are more of them, which leads to an increase in hysteresis.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The most commonly seen environmental sensitivity in hydrogels is a response to temperature.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Many polymers/hydrogels exhibit a temperature dependent phase transition, which can be classified as either an upper critical solution temperature (UCST) or lower critical solution temperature (LCST).
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] UCST polymers increase in their water-solubility at higher temperatures, which lead to UCST hydrogels transitioning from a gel (solid) to a solution (liquid) as the temperature is increased (similar to the melting point behavior of pure materials).
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] This phenomenon also causes UCST hydrogels to expand (increase their swell ratio) as temperature increases while they are below their UCST.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] However, polymers with LCSTs display an inverse (or negative) temperature-dependence, where their water-solubility decreases at higher temperatures.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] LCST hydrogels transition from a liquid solution to a solid gel as the temperature is increased, and they also shrink (decrease their swell ratio) as the temperature increases while they are above their LCST.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Applications can dictate for diverse thermal responses.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] For example, in the biomedical field, LCST hydrogels are being investigated as drug delivery systems due to being injectable (liquid) at room temp and then solidifying into a rigid gel upon exposure to the higher temperatures of the human body.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] There are many other stimuli that hydrogels can be responsive to, including: pH, glucose, electrical signals, light, pressure, ions, antigens, and more.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The mechanical properties of hydrogels can be fine-tuned in many ways beginning with attention to their hydrophobic properties.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Another method of modifying the strength or elasticity of hydrogels is to graft or surface coat them onto a stronger/stiffer support, or by making superporous hydrogel (SPH) composites, in which a cross-linkable matrix swelling additive is added.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Other additives, such as nanoparticles and microparticles, have been shown to significantly modify the stiffness and gelation temperature of certain hydrogels used in biomedical applications.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] While a hydrogel's mechanical properties can be tuned and modified through crosslink concentration and additives, these properties can also be enhanced or optimized for various applications through specific processing techniques.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] These techniques include electro-spinning, 3D/4D printing, self-assembly, and freeze-casting.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] One unique processing technique is through the formation of multi-layered hydrogels to create a spatially-varying matrix composition and by extension, mechanical properties.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] This can be done by polymerizing the hydrogel matrixes in a layer by layer fashion via UV polymerization.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] This technique can be useful in creating hydrogels that mimic articular cartilage, enabling a material with three separate zones of distinct mechanical properties.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Another emerging technique to optimize hydrogel mechanical properties is by taking advantage of the Hofmeister series.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Due to this phenomenon, through the addition of salt solution, the polymer chains of a hydrogel aggregate and crystallize, which increases the toughness of the hydrogel.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] This method, called "salting out", has been applied to poly(vinyl alcohol) hydrogels by adding a sodium sulfate salt solution.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Some of these processing techniques can be used synergistically with each other to yield optimal mechanical properties.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Directional freezing or freeze-casting is another method in which a directional temperature gradient is applied to the hydrogel is another way to form materials with anisotropic mechanical properties.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Utilizing both the freeze-casting and salting-out processing techniques on poly(vinyl alcohol) hydrogels to induce hierarchical morphologies and anisotropic mechanical properties.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Directional freezing of the hydrogels helps to align and coalesce the polymer chains, creating anisotropic array honeycomb tube-like structures while salting out the hydrogel yielded out a nano-fibril network on the surface of these honeycomb tube-like structures.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] While maintaining a water content of over 70%, these hydrogels' toughness values are well above those of water-free polymers such as polydimethylsiloxane (PDMS), Kevlar, and synthetic rubber.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The values also surpass the toughness of natural tendon and spider silk.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The yield stress of a hydrogel can be measured using the collapse test, a method commonly applied to materials suitable for 3D printing.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] In this test, a filament of hydrogel is printed on top of a series of plastic blocks with progressively increasing gaps between them.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] A side-view image of the filament is then taken, showing the angle the hydrogel filament forms with the vertical axis.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] This collapse angle provides a measurable indicator of the material's yield stress.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] (2017) established a set of equations to relate the collapse angle to the hydrogel's yield stress, providing a quantitative framework for assessing bioink shape fidelity in 3D bioprinting.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] These equations were later generalised in 2024 to account for non-symmetrical geometries and large deformations in hydrogels tested under similar collapse conditions.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Hydrogels are three-dimensional network structures with high hydrophilicity that can absorb and retain large amounts of water.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Due to their excellent biocompatibility, they are widely used in the field of biomaterials.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The main feature of hydrogels is their high water content, which is similar to the aqueous environment in biological systems, making them ideal for applications in tissue engineering, drug delivery, wound dressings, and artificial skin.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Hydrogels can be classified into natural and synthetic types.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Natural hydrogels, such as gelatin and chitosan, are derived from biological materials and offer good biodegradability and biocompatibility.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Synthetic hydrogels, on the other hand, typically have higher mechanical strength and tunability but may exhibit lower biocompatibility.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Additionally, hydrogels can be categorized as environmental-responsive or non-responsive based on their response to external stimuli.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Environmental-responsive hydrogels, which can react to changes in temperature, pH, or ion concentration, are particularly useful in drug delivery systems.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Due to their tunability, hydrogels continue to expand their applications in the biomedical field and are expected to play a crucial role in various medical applications in the future.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Implanted or injected hydrogels have the potential to support tissue regeneration by mechanical tissue support, localized drug or cell delivery, local cell recruitement or immunomodulation, or encapsulation of nanoparticles for local photothermal therapy or brachytherapy.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Polymeric drug delivery systems have overcome challenges due to their biodegradability, biocompatibility, and anti-toxicity.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Materials such as collagen, chitosan, cellulose, and poly (lactic-co-glycolic acid) have been implemented extensively for drug delivery to organs such as eye, nose, kidneys, lungs, intestines, skin and brain.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Hydrogels have been considered as vehicles for drug delivery.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] They can also be made to mimic animal mucosal tissues to be used for testing mucoadhesive properties.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] They have been examined for use as reservoirs in topical drug delivery; particularly ionic drugs, delivered by iontophoresis.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] Biomimetic physical barrier that separates T cells from tumors, potentially allowing them to regain strength before resuming immunotherapy.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] The dominant material for contact lenses are acrylate-siloxane hydrogels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/hydrogel] One of their most attractive properties is oxygen permeability, which is required since the cornea lacks vasculature.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] PEG is commonly incorporated into hydrogels which present a functional form for further use.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Polyethylene oxides (PEO's) have "very low single dose oral toxicity", on the order of tens of grams per kilogram of human body weight when ingested by mouth.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Because of its low toxicity, PEO is used in a variety of edible products.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] It is also used as a lubricating coating for various surfaces in aqueous and non-aqueous applications.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] The precursor to PEGs is ethylene oxide, which is hazardous.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Ethylene glycol and its ethers are nephrotoxic (poisonous to the kidneys) if applied to damaged skin.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] The United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA or US FDA) regards PEG as biologically inert and safe.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] A 2015 study appears to challenge the FDA's conclusion.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] In the study, a high-sensitivity ELISA assay detected anti-PEG antibodies in 72% of random blood plasma samples collected from 1990 to 1999.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] According to the study's authors, this result suggests that anti-PEG antibodies may be present, typically at low levels, in people who were never treated with PEGylated drugs.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Due to its ubiquity in many products and the large percentage of the population with antibodies to PEG, which indicates an allergic reaction, hypersensitive reactions to PEG are an increasing health concern.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Allergy to PEG is usually discovered after a person has been diagnosed with an allergy to several seemingly unrelated products—including processed foods, cosmetics, drugs, and other substances—that contain or were manufactured with PEG.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] PEG and PEO are liquids or low-melting solids, depending on their molecular weights.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] While PEG and PEO with different molecular weights find use in different applications and have different physical properties (e.g. viscosity) due to chain length effects, their chemical properties are nearly identical.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Different forms of PEG are also available, depending on the initiator used for the polymerization process – the most common initiator is a monofunctional methyl ether PEG, or methoxypoly(ethylene glycol), abbreviated mPEG.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Lower-molecular-weight PEGs are also available as purer oligomers, referred to as monodisperse, uniform, or discrete.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Very high-purity PEG has recently been shown to be crystalline, allowing the determination of a crystal structure by x-ray crystallography.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Since purification and separation of pure oligomers is difficult, the price for this type of quality is often 10–1000 fold that of polydisperse PEG.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] PEGs are also available with different geometries.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] The numbers that are often included in the names of PEGs indicate their average molecular weights (e.g. a PEG with *n* = 9 would have an average molecular weight of approximately 400 daltons, and would be labeled PEG 400).
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Most PEGs include molecules with a distribution of molecular weights (i.e. they are polydisperse).
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] The size distribution can be characterized statistically by its weight average molecular weight (*M*w) and its number average molecular weight (*M*n), the ratio of which is called the polydispersity index (*Đ*M).
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] *M*w and *M*n can be measured by mass spectrometry.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] PEGylation is the act of covalently coupling a PEG structure to another larger molecule, for example, a therapeutic protein, which is then referred to as a *PEGylated* protein.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] PEGylated interferon alfa-2a or alfa-2b are commonly used injectable treatments for hepatitis C infection.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] PEG is soluble in water, methanol, ethanol, acetonitrile, benzene, and dichloromethane, and is insoluble in diethyl ether and hexane.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] It is coupled to hydrophobic molecules to produce non-ionic surfactants.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] PEG and related polymers (PEG phospholipid constructs) are often sonicated when used in biomedical applications.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] However, as reported by Murali et al., PEG is very sensitive to sonolytic degradation and PEG degradation products can be toxic to mammalian cells.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] It is, thus, imperative to assess potential PEG degradation to ensure that the final material does not contain undocumented contaminants that can introduce artifacts into experimental results.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] PEGs and methoxypolyethylene glycols are manufactured by Dow Chemical under the trade name *Carbowax* for industrial use, and *Carbowax Sentry* for food and pharmaceutical use.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] They vary in consistency from liquid to solid, depending on the molecular weight, as indicated by a number following the name.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] They are used commercially in numerous applications, including foods, cosmetics, pharmaceutics, biomedicine, dispersing agents, solvents, ointments, suppository bases, as tablet excipients, and as laxatives.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Some specific groups are lauromacrogols, nonoxynols, octoxynols, and poloxamers.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] The production of polyethylene glycol was first reported in 1859.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Lourenço and Charles Adolphe Wurtz independently isolated products that were polyethylene glycols.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Polyethylene glycol is produced by the interaction of ethylene oxide with water, ethylene glycol, or ethylene glycol oligomers.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] The reaction is catalyzed by acidic or basic catalysts.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Ethylene glycol and its oligomers are preferable as a starting material instead of water because they allow the creation of polymers with a low polydispersity (narrow molecular weight distribution).
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Polymer chain length depends on the ratio of reactants.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Depending on the catalyst type, the mechanism of polymerization can be cationic or anionic.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] The anionic mechanism is preferable because it allows one to obtain PEG with a low polydispersity.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Polymerization of ethylene oxide is an exothermic process.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Overheating or contaminating ethylene oxide with catalysts, such as alkalis or metal oxides, can lead to runaway polymerization, which can end in an explosion after a few hours.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Polyethylene oxide, or high-molecular-weight polyethylene glycol, is synthesized by suspension polymerization.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] It is necessary to hold the growing polymer chain in solution in the course of the polycondensation process.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] The reaction is catalyzed by magnesium-, aluminium-, or calcium-organoelement compounds.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] To prevent coagulation of polymer chains from solution, chelating additives, such as dimethylglyoxime, are used.
[src:hydrogels-bio/polyethylene-glycol] Alkaline catalysts, such as sodium hydroxide (NaOH), potassium hydroxide (KOH), or sodium carbonate (Na2CO3), are used to prepare low-molecular-weight polyethylene glycol.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] A variety of different polymerization methods may be utilized for the synthesis of the polymer chains that make up hydrogels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Their properties depend on how these chains are crosslinked.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Crosslinking is the process of joining two or more polymer chains.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Both chemical and physical crosslinking exists.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] In addition, both natural polymers such as proteins or synthetic polymers with a high affinity for water may be used as starting materials when selecting a hydrogel.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Different crosslinking methods can be implemented for the design of a hydrogel.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] By definition, a crosslinked polymer gel is a macromolecule that solvent will not dissolve.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Due to the polymeric domains created by crosslinking in the gel microstructure, hydrogels are not homogenous within the selected solvent system.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The following sections summarize the chemical and physical methods by which hydrogels are crosslinked.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Hydrogen bonding is a strong intermolecular force that forms a special type of dipole-dipole attraction.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Hydrogen bonds form when a hydrogen atom bonded to a strongly electronegative atom is around another electronegative atom with a lone pair of electrons.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Hydrogen bonds are stronger than normal dipole-dipole interactions and dispersion forces but they remain weaker than covalent and ionic bonds.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] In hydrogels, structure and stability of water molecules are highly affected by the bonds.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The polar groups in the polymer strongly bind water molecules and form hydrogen bonds which also cause hydrophobic effects to occur.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] These hydrophobic effects can be exploited to design physically crosslinked hydrogels that exhibit self healing abilities.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The hydrophobic effects combined with the hydrophilic effects within the hydrogel structure can be balanced through dangling side chains that mediates the hydrogen bonding that occurs between two separate hydrogel pieces or across a ruptured hydrogel.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] A dangling side chain is a hydrocarbon chain side chains that branch off of the backbone of the polymer.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Attached to the side chain are polar functional groups.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The side chains "dangle" across the surface of the hydrogel, allowing it to interact with other functional groups and form new bonds.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The ideal side chain would be long and flexible so it could reach across the surface to react, but short enough to minimize steric hindrance and collapse from the hydrophobic effect.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The side chains need to keep both the hydrophobic and hydrophilic effects in balance.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] In a study performed by the University of California San Diego to compare healing ability, hydrogels of varying side chain lengths with similar crosslinking contents were compared and the results showed that healing ability of the hydrogels depends nonmonotonically on the side chain length.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] With shorter side chain lengths, there is limited reach of the carboxyl group which decreases the mediation of the hydrogen bonds across the interface.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] As the chain increases in length, the reach of the carboxyl group becomes more flexible and the hydrogen bonds can mediated.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] However, when a side chain length is too long, the interruption between the interaction of the carboxyl and amide groups that help to mediate the hydrogen bonds.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] It can also accumulate and collapse the hydrogel and prevent the healing from occurring.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Most self-healing hydrogels rely on electrostatic attraction to spontaneously create new bonds.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The electrostatic attraction can be masked using protonation of the polar functional groups.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] When the pH is raised the polar functional groups become deprotonated, freeing the polar functional group to react.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Since the hydrogels rely on electrostatic attraction for self-healing, the process can be affected by electrostatic screening.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The effects of a change in salinity can be modeled using the Gouy-Chapman-Stern theory Double Layer .
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] To calculate the Gouy–Chapmanm potential, the salinity factor must be calculated.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] These effects become important when considering the application of self-healing hydrogels to the medical field.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] They will be affected by the pH and salinity of blood.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] These effects also come into play during synthesis when trying to add large hydrophobes to a hydrophilic polymer backbone.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] A research group from the Istanbul Technical University has shown that large hydrophobes can be added by adding an electrolyte in a sufficient amount.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] During synthesis, the hydrophobes were held in micelles before attaching to the polymer backbone.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] By increasing the salinity of the solution, the micelles were able to grow and encompass more hydrophobes.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] If there are more hydrophobes in a micelle, then the solubility of the hydrophobe increases.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The increase in the solubility lead to an increase in the formation of hydrogels with large hydrophobes.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The surface tension (γ) of a material is directly related to its intramolecular and intermolecular forces.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The stronger the force, the greater the surface tension.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Where ΔvapU is the energy of vaporization, NA is the Avogadro constant, and a2 is the surface area per molecule.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] This equation also implies that the energy of vaporization affects surface tension.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] It is known that the stronger the force, the higher the energy of vaporization.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Surface tension can then be used to calculate surface energy (uσ).
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] where *T* is temperature and the system is at constant pressure and area.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Specifically for hydrogels, the free surface energy can be predicted using the Flory–Huggins free energy function for the hydrogels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] For hydrogels, surface tension plays a role in several additional characteristics including swelling ratio and stabilization.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Hydrogels have the remarkable ability to swell in water and aqueous solvents.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] During the process of swelling, surface instability can occur.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] This instability depends on the thickness of the hydrogel layers and the surface tension.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] A higher surface tension stabilizes the flat surface of the hydrogel, which is the outer-most layer.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] where *λ*h is the swelling ratio, *μ* is the chemical potential, *p* is pressure, *k*B is the Boltzmann constant, and *χ* and *N*v are unitless hydrogel constants.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] As swelling increases, mechanical properties generally suffer.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The surface deformation of hydrogels is important because it can result in self-induced cracking.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Each hydrogel has a characteristic wavelength of instability (*λ*) that depends on elastocapillary length.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] This length is calculated by dividing the surface tension (*γ*) by the elasticity (*μ*) of the hydrogel.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The greater the wavelength of instability, the greater the elastocapillary length of instability, which makes a material more prone to cracking.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] where *H* is the thickness of the hydrogel.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Some hydrogels are able to respond to stimuli and their surrounding environments.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Examples of these stimuli include light, temperature, pH, and electrical fields.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Hydrogels that are temperature sensitive are known as thermogels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Thermo-responsive hydrogels undergo reversible, thermally induced phase transition upon reaching either the upper or lower critical solution temperature.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] By definition, a crosslinked polymer gel is a macromolecule that cannot dissolve.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Due to the polymeric domains created by crosslinking, in the gel microstructure, hydrogels are not homogenous within the solvent system in which they are placed into.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Swelling of the network, however, does occur in the presence of a proper solvent.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Voids in the microstructure of the gel where crosslinking agent or monomer has aggregated during polymerization can cause solvent to diffuse into or out of the hydrogel.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The microstructure of hydrogel therefore are not constant, and imperfections occur where water from outside of the gel can accumulate these voids.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] This process is temperature dependent, and solvent behavior depends on whether the solvent-gel system has reached, or surpassed, the critical solution temperature (LCST).
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The LCST defines a boundary between which a gel or polymer chain will separate solvent into one or two phases.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The spinodial and binodial regions of a polymer-solvent phase diagram represent the energetic favorability of the hydrogel becoming miscible in solution or separating into two phases.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Self-healing hydrogels encompass a wide range of applications.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] With a high biocompatibility, hydrogels are useful for a number of medical applications.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Hydrogels are created from crosslinked polymers that are water-insoluble.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Polymer hydrogels absorb significant amounts of aqueous solutions, and therefore have a high water content.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] This high water content makes hydrogel more similar to living body tissues than any other material for tissue regeneration.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Additionally, polymer scaffolds using self-healing hydrogels are structurally similar to the extracellular matrices of many of the tissues.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Scaffolds act as three-dimensional artificial templates in which the tissue targeted for reconstruction is cultured to grow onto.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The high porosity of hydrogels allows for the diffusion of cells during migration, as well as the transfer of nutrients and waste products away from cellular membranes.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Scaffolds are subject to harsh processing conditions during tissue culturing.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] These include mechanical stimulation to promote cellular growth, a process which places stress on the scaffold structure.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] This stress may lead to localized rupturing of the scaffold which is detrimental to the reconstruction process.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] In a self-healing hydrogel scaffold, ruptured scaffolds have the ability for localized self-repair of their damaged three-dimensional structure.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Current research is exploring the effectiveness of using various types of hydrogel scaffolds for tissue engineering and regeneration including synthetic hydrogels, biological hydrogels, and biohybrid hydrogels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] In 2019, researchers Biplab Sarkar and Vivek Kumar of the New Jersey Institute of Technology developed a self-assembling peptide hydrogel that has proven successful in increasing blood vessel regrowth and neuron survival in rats affected by Traumatic Brain Injuries (TBI).
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] By adapting the hydrogel to closely resemble brain tissue and injecting it into the injured areas of the brain, the researchers' studies have shown improved mobility and cognition after only a week of treatment.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] If trials continued to prove successful, this peptide hydrogel may be approved for human trials and eventual widespread use in the medical community as a treatment for TBIs.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] This hydrogel also has the potential to be adapted to other forms of tissue in the human body, and promote regeneration and recovery from other injuries.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Polyethylene glycol(PEG) polymers are synthetic materials that can be crosslinked to form hydrogels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] PEG hydrogels are not toxic to the body, do not elicit an immune response, and have been approved by the US Food and Drug Administration for clinical use.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The surfaces of PEG polymers are easily modified with peptide sequences that can attract cells for adhesion and could therefore be used for tissue regeneration.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Poly (2-hydroxyethyl methacrylate) (PHEMA) hydrogels can be combined with rosette nanotubes (RNTs).
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] RNTs can emulate skin structures such as collagen and keratin and self-assemble when injected into the body.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] This type of hydrogel is being explored for use in skin regeneration and has shown promising results such as fibroblast and keratinocyte proliferation.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Both of these cell types are crucial for the production of skin components.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Biological hydrogels are derived from preexisting components of body tissues such as collagen, hyaluronic acid (HA), or fibrin.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Collagen, HA, and fibrin are components that occur naturally in the extracellular matrix of mammals.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Collagen is the main structural component in tissues and it already contains cell-signaling domains that can promote cell growth.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] In order to mechanically enhance collagen into a hydrogel, it must be chemically crosslinked, crosslinked using UV light or temperature, or mixed with other polymers.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Collagen hydrogels would be nontoxic and biocompatible.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Hybrid hydrogels combine synthetic and biological materials and take advantage of the best properties of each.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Synthetic polymers are easily customizable and can be tailored for specific functions such as biocompatibility.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Biological polymers such as peptides also have adventitious properties such as specificity of binding and high affinity for certain cells and molecules.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] A hybrid of these two polymer types allows for the creation of hydrogels with novel properties.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] An example of a hybrid hydrogel would include a synthetically created polymer with several peptide domains.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Peptide-based self-healing hydrogels may be selectively grown onto nanofiber material which can then incorporated into the desired reconstructive tissue target.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The hydrogel framework is then chemically modified to promote cell adhesion to the nanofiber peptide scaffold.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Because the growth of the extracellular matrix scaffold is pH dependent, the materials selected must be factored for pH response when selecting the scaffolding material.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The swelling and bioadhesion of hydrogels can be controlled based on the fluid environment they are introduced to in the body.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] These properties make them excellent for use as controlled drug delivery devices.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Where the hydrogel adheres in the body will be determined by its chemistry and reactions with the surrounding tissues.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] If introduced by mouth, the hydrogel could adhere to anywhere in the gastrointestinal tract including the mouth, the stomach, the small intestine, or the colon.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Adhesion in a specifically targeted region will cause for a localized drug delivery and an increased concentration of the drug taken up by the tissues.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Smart hydrogels are sensitive to stimuli such as changes in temperature or pH.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Changes in the environment alter the swelling properties of the hydrogels and can cause them to increase or decrease the release of the drug impregnated into the fibers.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] An example of this would be hydrogels that release insulin in the presence of high glucose levels in the bloodstream.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] These glucose sensitive hydrogels are modified with the enzyme glucose oxidase.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] In the presence of glucose, the glucose oxidase will catalyze a reaction that ends in increased levels of H+.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] These H+ ions raise the pH of the surrounding environment and could therefore cause a change in a smart hydrogel that would initiate the release of insulin.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Dangling type side chain self-healing hydrogels are activated by changes in the relative acidity of solution they are in.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Depending on user specified application, side chains may be selectively used in self-healing hydrogels as pH indicators.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] If a specified functional group chain end with a low pKa, such as a carboxylic acid, is subject to a neutral pH conditions, water will deprotonate the acidic chain end, activating the chain ends.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Crosslinking or what is known as self-healing will begin, causing two or more separated hydrogels to fuse into one.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Research into the use self-healing hydrogels has revealed an effective method for mitigating acid spills through the ability to selectively crosslink under acidic conditions.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] In a testing done by the University of California San Diego, various surfaces were coated with self healing hydrogels and then mechanically damaged with 300 micrometer wide cracks with the coatings healing the crack within seconds upon exposure of low pH buffers.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] The hydrogels also can adhere to various plastics due to hydrophobic interactions.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Both findings suggest the use of these hydrogels as a sealant for vessels containing corrosive acids.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] No commercial applications currently exist for implementation of this technology.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] Drying of hydrogels under controlled circumstances may yield xerogels and aerogels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] A xerogel is a solid that retains significant porosity (15-50%) with a very small pore size (1–10 nm).
[src:hydrogels-bio/self-healing-hydrogels] In an aerogel, the porosity is somewhat higher and the pores are more than an order of magnitude larger, resulting in an ultra-low-density material with a low thermal conductivity and an almost translucent, smoke-like appearance.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Causes may include venous insufficiency, heart failure, kidney problems, low protein levels, liver problems, deep vein thrombosis, infections, kwashiorkor, angioedema, certain medications, and lymphedema.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] It may also occur in people who are immobilized (as by stroke, spinal cord injury, or aging), even temporarily (as by prolonged sitting or standing), and during menstruation or pregnancy.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] The condition is more concerning if it starts suddenly, or if pain or shortness of breath is present.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Treatment depends on the underlying cause.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] If the underlying mechanism involves sodium retention, decreased salt intake and a diuretic may be used.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Elevating the legs and support stockings may be useful for edema of the legs.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Older people are more commonly affected.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] The word is from the Ancient Greek οἴδημα *oídēma* ('swelling').
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Edema will occur in specific organs as part of inflammation, tendinitis or pancreatitis.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Certain organs develop edema through tissue specific mechanisms.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] A rise in hydrostatic pressure occurs in cardiac failure.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] A fall in osmotic pressure occurs in nephrotic syndrome and liver failure.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Causes of edema that are generalized to the whole body can cause edema in multiple organs and peripherally.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] For example, severe heart failure can cause pulmonary edema, pleural effusions, ascites and peripheral edema.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Such severe systemic edema is called anasarca.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] In rare cases, a parvovirus B19 infection may cause generalized edema.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Although a low plasma oncotic pressure is widely cited for the edema of nephrotic syndrome, most physicians note that the edema may occur before there is any significant protein in the urine (proteinuria) or fall in plasma protein level.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Most forms of nephrotic syndrome are due to biochemical and structural changes in the basement membrane of capillaries in the kidney glomeruli, and these changes occur, if to a lesser degree, in the vessels of most other tissues of the body.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Thus the resulting increase in permeability that leads to protein in the urine can explain the edema if all other vessels are more permeable as well.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] As well as the previously mentioned conditions, edema often occurs during the late stages of pregnancy in some women.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] This is more common with those of a history of pulmonary problems or poor circulation also being intensified if arthritis is already present in that particular woman.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Women who already have arthritic problems most often have to seek medical help for pain caused from over-reactive swelling.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Edema that occurs during pregnancy are usually found in the lower part of the leg, usually from the calf down.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Hydrops fetalis is a condition in a baby characterized by an accumulation of fluid in at least two body compartments.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] The pumping force of the heart should help to keep a normal pressure within the blood vessels.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] If the heart begins to fail (a condition known as congestive heart failure), the pressure changes can cause very severe water retention.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] In this condition water retention is mostly visible in the legs, feet and ankles, but water also collects in the lungs, where it causes a chronic cough.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] This condition is usually treated with diuretics; otherwise, the water retention may cause breathing problems and additional stress on the heart.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Another cause of severe water retention is kidney failure, where the kidneys are no longer able to filter fluid out of the blood and turn it into urine.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Kidney disease often starts with inflammation, for instance in the case of diseases such as nephrotic syndrome or lupus.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] This type of water retention is usually visible in the form of swollen legs and ankles.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Cirrhosis (scarring) of the liver is a common cause of edema in the legs and abdominal cavity.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Phlebetic lymphedema (or phlebolymphedema) is seen in untreated chronic venous insufficiency and is the most common type of edema (approx.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] It is a combination venous/lymphatic disorder that originates in defective "leaky" veins that allows the blood to back flow (venous reflux), slowing the return of the blood to the heart (venous stasis).
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] The venous pressure in the legs changes dramatically while standing compared to lying down.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] How much pressure there is depends on the person's height; in the average adult person, it is 8 mm Hg while lying down and 100 mm Hg while standing.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] In venous insufficiency, venous stasis results in abnormally high venous pressure (venous hypertension) and greater permeability of blood capillaries (capillary hyperpermeability), to drain the blood through the lymphatic system.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] The lymphatic system slowly removes excess fluid and proteins from the veins in the lower legs towards the upper body; however, as it is not as efficient as an unimpaired circulatory system, swelling (edema) is visible, particularly in the ankles and lower legs.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] The chronic increased fluid in the lymphatic system and capillary hyperpermeability causes an inflammatory response which leads to tissue fibrosis of both veins and lymphatic system, opening of arteriovenous shunts, all of which then worsens the condition in a vicious cycle.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Swollen legs, feet and ankles are common in late pregnancy.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] The problem is partly caused by the weight of the uterus on the major veins of the pelvis.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] It usually clears up after delivery of the baby, and is mostly not a cause for concern, though it should always be reported to a doctor.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Lack of exercise is another common cause of water retention in the legs.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Exercise helps the leg veins work against gravity to return blood to the heart.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] If blood travels too slowly and starts to pool in the leg veins, the pressure can force fluid out of the leg capillaries into the tissue spaces.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] The capillaries may break, leaving small blood marks under the skin.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] The veins themselves can become swollen, painful and distorted – a condition known as varicose veins.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Causes of bilateral pedal edema: (after exclusion of cardiac, renal, heart, liver and thyroid disorders, malnutrition or malabsorption).
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Muscle action is needed not only to keep blood flowing through the veins but also to stimulate the lymphatic system to fulfill its "overflow" function.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Long-haul airplane flights, lengthy bed-rest, immobility caused by disability and so on, are all potential causes of water retention.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Even very small exercises such as rotating ankles or wiggling toes can help to reduce peripheral edema.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Certain medications are prone to causing water retention.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] These include estrogens, thereby including drugs for hormone replacement therapy or the combined oral contraceptive pill, as well as non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs and beta-blockers.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Premenstrual water retention, causing bloating and breast tenderness, is common.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] 6. changes in the water-retaining properties of the tissues themselves.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Raised hydrostatic pressure often reflects retention of water and sodium by the kidneys.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Generation of interstitial fluid is regulated by the forces of the Starling equation.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Hydrostatic pressure within blood vessels tends to cause water to filter out into the tissue.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] This leads to a difference in protein concentration between blood plasma and tissue.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] As a result, the colloidal or oncotic pressure of the higher level of protein in the plasma tends to draw water back into the blood vessels from the tissue.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Starling's equation states that the rate of leakage of fluid is determined by the difference between the two forces and also by the permeability of the vessel wall to water, which determines the rate of flow for a given force imbalance.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Most water leakage occurs in capillaries or post capillary venules, which have a semi-permeable membrane wall that allows water to pass more freely than protein.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Changes in the variables in Starling's equation can contribute to the formation of edemas either by an increase in hydrostatic pressure within the blood vessel, a decrease in the oncotic pressure within the blood vessel or an increase in vessel wall permeability.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] It allows water to flow more freely and it reduces the colloidal or oncotic pressure difference by allowing protein to leave the vessel more easily.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Another set of vessels known as the lymphatic system acts like an "overflow" and can return much excess fluid to the bloodstream.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] But even the lymphatic system can be overwhelmed, and if there is simply too much fluid, or if the lymphatic system is congested, then the fluid will remain in the tissues, causing swellings in legs, ankles, feet, abdomen or any other part of the body.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] The excessive extracellular fluid (interstitial fluid) in edemas is to a substantial degree caused by an increased permeability of the smallest blood vessels (capillaries).
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] This permeability is modulated by numerous biochemical chain reactions and can therefore be unbalanced by many influences.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Involved in these processes are, among others, the transmembrane proteins occludin, claudins, tight junction protein ZO-1, cadherins, catenins and actinin, which are directed by intracellular signal chains, in particular in connection with the enzyme protein kinase C.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Edema may be described as **pitting edema** or **non-pitting edema**.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Pitting edema is when, after pressure is applied to a small area, the indentation persists after the release of the pressure.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Peripheral pitting edema, as shown in the illustration, is the more common type, resulting from water retention.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] It can be caused by systemic diseases, pregnancy in some women, either directly or as a result of heart failure, or local conditions such as varicose veins, thrombophlebitis, insect bites, and dermatitis.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Non-pitting edema is observed when the indentation does not persist.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] It is associated with such conditions as lymphedema, lipedema, and myxedema.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Edema caused by malnutrition defines kwashiorkor, an acute form of childhood protein-energy malnutrition characterized by edema, irritability, anorexia, ulcerating dermatoses, and an enlarged liver with fatty infiltrates.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Vein obstruction causes facial edema while lying down to sleep.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] After being upright all day, the swelling disappears.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] When possible, treatment involves resolving the underlying cause.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Many cases of heart or kidney disease are treated with diuretics.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Treatment may also involve positioning the affected body parts to improve drainage.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] For example, swelling in feet or ankles may be reduced by having the person lie down in bed or sit with the feet propped up on cushions.
[src:hydrogels-bio/swelling-medical] Intermittent pneumatic compression can be used to pressurize tissue in a limb, forcing fluids — both blood and lymph — to flow out of the compressed area.
